metadata.name: A plateful of noodles #6
metadata.description:
This is a grid based collision experiment.

The work is built entirely on thi.ng/umbrella libraries and template:

https://github.com/thi-ng/fxhash-tpl

Keyboard shortcuts

- space bar : pause/resume animation
- 2 : render @ 2 x resolution
- 4 : render @ 4 x resolution
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution
- s : download canvas as SVG @ current resolution; This can be used with a plotter.

metadata.name: Plantlets #18
metadata.description:
It all started with amazing work of Julien Leonard (https://twitter.com/julleor) and his blogposts explaining some of his explorations. 

All these prompted me to explore the basically a circle packing process combined with pattern replication in my own directions and style. I really liked the results and here I am with a project that is able to produce a wide variety of shapes from ivy plants spreading a cross a wall to city maps.

In this project the color palettes are produced algorithmically so please forgive me when some of them are not that pretty. :)


Keyboard shortcuts

- 1 : render @ 1024 x 1024 resolution
- 2 : render @ 2 x resolution
- 3 : render @ 3 x resolution
- 4 : render @ 4 x resolution
- c : show/hide the clipping layer 
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution

metadata.name: Kathedral #43
metadata.description:
This piece is another exploration of angle preserving transformations. This time I use some complex plane transformations, one of which is z^2.

The rendering is done in SVG and you can zoom in as much as the browser allows. It also allows you to export a png version and implements 3 aspect ratios: Portrait, Square and Landscape.

Keyboard shortcuts
1 - 9: export at resolution n*600 x n*600*AR (AR aspect ratio)
s    : export the SVG file
x    : export a 8X png file

metadata.name: Pompeii Sunset #60
metadata.description:
What happens when you take a handful of particles, make them move on various trajectories and draw lines between them? This!

The piece is built entirely on thi.ng/umbrella libraries and template:

https://github.com/thi-ng/fxhash-tpl

Initial resolution is the screen resolution. Although the piece is supposed to look the same no matter the resolution, we all know this is not possible. But I think I made a good job at it.

Keyboard shortcuts

- 2 : download png @ 2 x resolution
- 4 : download png @ 4 x resolution
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution

metadata.name: Universal Rayhatcher #398
metadata.description:
# What is this?

This is 6942 characters of highly experimental code.

This is a version of my rayhatcher framework (see https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/rayhatching-evolution) that can do literally everything. Or, at least anything you can do within 512 characters of Javascript code. Which is slightly more than a mortal brain can comprehend.

This is my answer to the question: What is the least restrictive set of parameters for fx(params)?

# Should I be minting this?

Depends if you know and like building SDF formulas. Otherwise probably not. Like I said, this is highly experimental code. But it's definitely worth checking the collection and/or secondary for cool stuff that is already minted.

# How does it work?

The minter designs an SDF (Signed Distance Function) which is rendered using my rayhatcher algorithm. They then use the SDF formula in the SDF Code parameter. It's not very complicated, just efficient.

You can press "h" to load the documentation and read about how everything works. Or you can press "d" to read the dev docs. 

# Anything else?

Don't forget that the "Title Seed" param also becomes the "Title" feature of the mint, so make it count.

The params, including the SDF code actually get saved on-chain. Even better, all params and the entire code required to reproduce the image are included in the SVG when saved. See https://twitter.com/piterpasma/status/1649071912742420482 .

metadata.name: Artifice #248
metadata.description:
This series is is about playful obfuscation.

The fxtext article linked on the main profect goes more in-depth into what is meant by that, as well as the events that led to this collection.

5640 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries. Palettes make up a third of the code.

In live mode:
‘S’ : save as png (3000 × 3600)
’V’ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=p’ : paper grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 9000 ×10600 (Chrome only, and may take a moment)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append “&g=p&h=t” to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save a png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: EDDY #117
metadata.description:
An eddy is a circular movement of water counter to a main current. It reminds me of innovations in art, like a small countercurrent to the mainstream, surfacing new techniques and aesthetics. 

I hope that EDDY will brighten your days with its playful swirl of colors, inspired by the sea, the sky, the birds, and post-impressionist paintings.

Keyboard Controls:
[F] Fill the window.
[S] Save the current view in live mode as an image (default 1125x1500px).
[1] [2] [4] [6] Change resolution, 1.5K to 9K.
[R] Reverse course.

Made with p5js and shaders.

Created by elsif, 2022.12.

metadata.name: aprendizajes #133
metadata.description:
aprendizajes is a generative art project that pays a tribute to the process of learning. 25% of primary proceeds go to Save The Children. Full description of the artwork+instructions here: https://www.iillucid.com/aprendizajes/

The artwork allows the user to:

* Change resolution: press 'd' followed by any number from 1 to 9 to add that amount to the pixel density. If you get a black screen you have surpassed what your graphics card can handle: press d + 0 to reset the pixel density. You can fine tune pressing d followed by + or - (+/- 0.5).
* Save image: press 's' to save the current image as png. For a higher resolution png, 1st increase the resolution using 'd' and then save the image with 's'.
* Tune image parameters: press 'z' (brightness), 'x' (contrast), 'g' (gamma), 'b' (blur) followed by + or - to adjust. Toggle tuning with 'a'. Press 'n' then + or - to adjust amount of noise.
* Redraw: 'r' (changes how lines are drawn)

It is recommended to read the full instructions on the article.

metadata.name: Concrete #135
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksjø (1910–1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksjø designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksjø’s aim was to “soften” modernist architecture. He invented «Natural Concrete», a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions—using code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksjø: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‘S’ to save an image at current resolution or ‘P’ to save a high-resolution file at 6000×6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau · Made with p5.js & glsl · Oslo, 2021

metadata.name: Wondering #45
metadata.description:
The work contains a fluid simulation. I put random forces into the simulation and let it run 500 steps to create a flow field and then use it to generate the visuals. 

I choose fluid simulation instead of curl noise or any other noise function because I believe the fluid simulation could generate a movement that's more dynamic and organic. The result is a combination of big and small vortices.


This piece requires WebGL2 to run, please check and make sure this runs on your device in advance. Also you can press the spacebar to toggle the camera control.
